# 🐳 Docker Swarm Node.js Project with Autoscaling

A complete production-ready Docker Swarm project with Node.js microservices, Redis caching, and **built-in autoscaling** (no external tools needed!).

## 📋 What is Docker Swarm?

Docker Swarm turns multiple Docker servers into one big virtual server. It helps you:
- Run multiple copies of your app for high availability
- Automatically restart crashed containers (self-healing)
- Distribute traffic between containers (load balancing)
- Update your app without downtime (rolling updates)
- **Automatically scale services based on CPU usage** (autoscaling)

## 🏗️ Project Architecture

```
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                    DOCKER SWARM CLUSTER                      │
│                                                              │
│  ┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐    │
│  │                   API GATEWAY (Port 8080)            │    │
│  │              Routes requests to services             │    │
│  └───────────────┬─────────────────┬───────────────────┘    │
│                  │                 │                         │
│         ┌────────▼────────┐   ┌─────▼──────────┐             │
│         │  USER SERVICE   │   │ PRODUCT SERVICE│             │
│         │   Port 3001     │   │   Port 3002    │             │
│         │  (3 replicas)   │   │  (3 replicas)  │             │
│         └────────┬────────┘   └─────┬──────────┘             │
│                  │                 │                         │
│                  └─────────┬───────┘                         │
│                            │                                 │
│                    ┌───────▼───────┐                         │
│                    │ REDIS (Cache) │                         │
│                    │   Port 6379   │                         │
│                    └───────────────┘                         │
│                                                              │
│  ┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐    │
│  │              AUTOSCALER (Built-in)                   │    │
│  │    Monitors CPU every 30 seconds                    │    │
│  │    Scales UP when CPU > threshold                   │    │
│  │    Scales DOWN when CPU < threshold                 │    │
│  └─────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘    │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
```

## 🚀 Quick Start (5 Minutes)

### Prerequisites
- Docker Desktop installed
- Node.js (optional - Docker handles this)

### Step 1: Clone or Create Project
```bash
mkdir my-swarm-project
cd my-swarm-project
```

### Step 2: Initialize Docker Swarm
```bash
# Turn on Swarm mode
docker swarm init
```

### Step 3: Create Secrets
```bash
# Create API secrets
echo "my-api-key-123" | docker secret create api_key -
echo "my-jwt-secret-456" | docker secret create jwt_secret -
```

### Step 4: Build and Deploy
```bash
# Build all Docker images
docker compose build

# Deploy to Swarm
docker stack deploy -c docker-compose.yaml demo

# Check if running
docker service ls
```

## 📊 Service Details

| Service | Replicas | Port | Purpose |
|---------|----------|------|---------|
| API Gateway | 2 | 8080 | Entry point, routes requests |
| User Service | 3 | 3001 | User management with Redis cache |
| Product Service | 3 | 3002 | Product management with Redis lock |
| Redis | 1 | 6379 | Caching and distributed locking |
| Autoscaler | 1 | - | CPU-based autoscaling |

## 🔄 Service Discovery

Services communicate by **service name**, not IP addresses:

| From | To | Uses URL |
|------|-----|----------|
| API Gateway | User Service | `http://user-service:3001` |
| API Gateway | Product Service | `http://product-service:3002` |
| User Service | Redis | `redis://demo_redis:6379` |
| Product Service | Redis | `redis://demo_redis:6379` |

## 📝 Useful Commands

### Service Management

```bash
# List all services
docker service ls

# List all containers in a service
docker service ps demo_product-service

# Scale a service manually
docker service scale demo_product-service=5

# Force restart a service
docker service update --force demo_api-gateway

# Remove entire stack
docker stack rm demo
```

### Monitoring Commands

```bash
# Watch service status in real-time
while true; do clear; docker service ls; sleep 3; done

# Watch product service replicas
while true; do clear; docker service ls | grep product-service; sleep 2; done

# Check container health
docker ps --format "table {{.Names}}\t{{.Status}}"

# View service logs
docker service logs demo_api-gateway --tail=50
docker service logs demo_product-service -f
```

### Testing Endpoints

```bash
# Test API Gateway
curl http://localhost:8080/

# Get all users
curl http://localhost:8080/users

# Get all products
curl http://localhost:8080/products

# Check product stock
curl http://localhost:8080/products/1/stock

# Buy a product (with Redis lock)
curl -X POST http://localhost:8080/products/1/buy \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -d '{"quantity":1}'

# Check secrets
curl http://localhost:8080/check-secrets

# Health check
curl http://localhost:8080/health
```

## 🔒 Redis Distributed Lock

**Problem:** Multiple users buying same product simultaneously can oversell stock.

**Solution:** Redis lock ensures only ONE purchase happens at a time.

### Test Concurrent Purchases
```bash
# Run 3 purchases simultaneously (only 1 succeeds, 2 get lock error)
for i in {1..3}; do
    curl -X POST http://localhost:8080/products/1/buy \
      -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
      -d '{"quantity":1}' &
done
wait
```

## 📈 Autoscaling (Built-in, No External Tools!)

Your autoscaler monitors CPU every 30 seconds and scales automatically:

### How Autoscaling Works

```
                    START
                      │
                      ▼
              Install tools (apk add...)
                      │
                      ▼
        ┌─────────────────────────────────────┐
        │         FOREVER LOOP                │
        │                                     │
        │  1. Find product container          │
        │  2. Get its CPU %                   │
        │  3. Get current replica count       │
        │  4. Log: "CPU=8% REPLICAS=2"        │
        │                                     │
        │  5. Is CPU > 5%?                    │
        │     YES → Scale UP (+1 container)   │
        │            Wait 120 seconds         │
        │                                     │
        │  6. Is CPU < 2%?                    │
        │     YES → Scale DOWN (-1 container) │
        │            Wait 120 seconds         │
        │                                     │
        │  7. Wait 30 seconds                 │
        │     └──→ Back to step 1             │
        └─────────────────────────────────────┘
```

### Autoscaling Configuration

| Parameter | Value | Meaning |
|-----------|-------|---------|
| Scale UP threshold | CPU > 5% | Add a replica when CPU exceeds 5% |
| Scale DOWN threshold | CPU < 2% | Remove a replica when CPU drops below 2% |
| Min replicas | 1 | Never go below 1 container |
| Max replicas | 8 | Never go above 8 containers |
| Check interval | 30 seconds | Check CPU every 30 seconds |
| Cooldown period | 120 seconds | Wait 2 minutes before next scaling |

### Generate Load to Test Autoscaling

```bash
# Heavy load test (2 minutes)
echo "Starting load test at $(date)"
end=$((SECONDS+120))
count=0
while [ $SECONDS -lt $end ]; do
  for i in {1..50}; do
    curl -s -X POST http://localhost:8080/products/1/buy \
      -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
      -d '{"quantity":1}' > /dev/null 2>&1 &
  done
  count=$((count + 50))
  if [ $((count % 500)) -eq 0 ]; then
    echo "Sent $count requests..."
    docker stats --no-stream --format "CPU: {{.CPUPerc}}" \
      $(docker ps -q --filter name=product-service) 2>/dev/null | head -1
  fi
  sleep 0.5
done
wait
echo "Load test complete! Sent $count requests"
```

### Monitor Autoscaling

```bash
# Watch autoscaler logs
docker service logs -f demo_autoscaler

# Watch replica count
while true; do clear; docker service ls | grep product-service; sleep 2; done

# Watch CPU usage
while true; do
  clear
  docker stats --no-stream $(docker ps -q --filter name=product-service) 2>/dev/null
  sleep 2
done
```

### Expected Autoscaler Output

```
CPU=0.00 REPLICAS=3
CPU=5.86 REPLICAS=3
Scaling UP to 4 replicas
demo_product-service scaled to 4
CPU=2.10 REPLICAS=4
CPU=0.00 REPLICAS=4
Scaling DOWN to 3 replicas
demo_product-service scaled to 3
```

## 🔄 Rolling Updates (Zero Downtime)

Update your service without any downtime - Swarm updates containers one by one.

### Step 1: Build new version
```bash
docker build -t swarm-demo/gateway:v2 ./services/ApiGateway
```

### Step 2: Update the service
```bash
docker service update --image swarm-demo/gateway:v2 demo_api-gateway
```

### Step 3: Monitor rolling update
```bash
while true; do
  clear
  docker service ps demo_api-gateway
  sleep 2
done
```

### Step 4: Rollback if needed
```bash
docker service rollback demo_api-gateway
```

## 💊 Health Checks

Each service has a `/health` endpoint. Docker Swarm automatically restarts unhealthy containers.

### Check Health Status
```bash
# See all containers with health status
docker ps --format "table {{.Names}}\t{{.Status}}"

# Expected output shows (healthy)
demo_product-service.1    Up 2 minutes (healthy)
demo_product-service.2    Up 2 minutes (healthy)
demo_user-service.1       Up 2 minutes (healthy)
```

### Test Health Endpoints
```bash
# API Gateway health
curl http://localhost:8080/health

# Direct service health (from inside container)
docker exec <container-id> wget -q -O- http://localhost:3002/health
```

## 🔐 Secrets Management

Secrets are encrypted and only accessible to authorized services.

### Create Secrets
```bash
echo "my-api-key" | docker secret create api_key -
echo "my-jwt-secret" | docker secret create jwt_secret -
```

### List Secrets
```bash
docker secret ls
```

### Verify Secrets in Container
```bash
docker exec <container-id> ls -la /run/secrets/
docker exec <container-id> cat /run/secrets/api_key
```

### Remove Secrets (if needed)
```bash
docker secret rm api_key jwt_secret
```

## 🛠️ Troubleshooting

### Service Not Starting
```bash
# Check service logs
docker service logs demo_api-gateway --tail=50

# Check service tasks
docker service ps demo_api-gateway

# Force restart
docker service update --force demo_api-gateway
```

### Exit Code 137 (Out of Memory)
- Increase memory limits in docker-compose.yaml
- Or remove memory limits temporarily

### Container Shows (unhealthy)
- Ensure `/health` endpoint exists in your code
- Check if curl is installed in Dockerfile: `RUN apk add --no-cache curl`

### Clean Everything and Start Fresh
```bash
# Remove stack
docker stack rm demo

# Leave swarm
docker swarm leave --force

# Remove images
docker rmi $(docker images -q) 2>/dev/null

# Re-initialize
docker swarm init

# Re-create secrets
echo "my-api-key-123" | docker secret create api_key -
echo "my-jwt-secret-456" | docker secret create jwt_secret -

# Rebuild and deploy
docker compose build
docker stack deploy -c docker-compose.yaml demo
```

